03680nam a22004935i 9780520969926DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209699267 a10.1525/97805209699262doi  a(DE-B1597)520563  a(OCoLC)1028583325  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPER0041202bisacsh1 aTsika, Noah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aTraumatic Imprints :bCinema, Military Psychiatry, and the Aftermath of War /cNoah Tsika. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Documenting the "Residue of Battle" -- t1. "Imaging the Mind": Military Psychiatry Meets Documentary Film -- t2. Solemn Venues: War Trauma and the Expanding Nontheatrical Realm -- t3. Selling "Psycho Films": Trauma Cinema and the Military-Industrial Complex -- t4. Psychodocudramatics: Role-Playing War Trauma from the Hospital to Hollywood -- t5. "Casualties of the Spirit": Let There Be Light and Its Contexts -- tConclusion: Traumatic Returns -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForced to contend with unprecedented levels of psychological trauma during World War II, the United States military began sponsoring a series of nontheatrical films designed to educate and even rehabilitate soldiers and civilians alike. Traumatic Imprints traces the development of psychiatric and psychotherapeutic approaches to wartime trauma by the United States military, along with links to formal and narrative developments in military and civilian filmmaking. Offering close readings of a series of films alongside analysis of period scholarship in psychiatry and bolstered by research in trauma theory and documentary studies, Noah Tsika argues that trauma was foundational in postwar American culture. Examining wartime and postwar debates about the use of cinema as a vehicle for studying, publicizing, and even what has been termed "working through" war trauma, this book is an original contribution to scholarship on the military-industrial complex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969926423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520969926.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles